    en: "Most contracts in NY are enforceable even without a written agreement. But some have to be in writing to be enforceable in court. NY General Obligations Law section 5-701 (the Statute of Frauds) lists the categories. The main ones are: (1) any agreement that cannot be performed within one year, (2) a promise to pay someone else's debt, (3) finder or business-broker fee agreements, and (4) credit agreements over $50,000 not for personal use. Real estate sales and leases over one year fall under a separate writing rule at GOL 5-703. Sales of goods over $500 are covered by UCC 2-201. An email exchange that captures the key terms can satisfy the writing requirement under NY's Electronic Signatures and Records Act."
